<H2><U>
Native American Legends About Foxes
</u></H2>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.ilhawaii.net/~stony/lore26.html
">The Hungry Fox and the Boastful Suitor</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Iroquois Indian story about Fox making a fool out of a boastful man.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><B><A HREF="
http://www.idahoptv.org/outdoors/shows/triptothemoon/wolffox.cfm
">The Wolf, the Fox, the Bobcat and the Cougar</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Native American legend about a fox spirit that helped the Shoshone-Bannocks defeat the warlike Little People.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://legends.knet.on.ca/part3.htm
">Iyash and Old Lady Fox</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Severn Ojibwe legend about a hero passing a strange test to earn the advice of a wise Fox-Woman.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.mpm.edu/wirp/ICW-138.html#fox
">A Fox Tale</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Menominee legend about Fox tricking Wolf out of some maple sugar.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><B><A HREF="
http://www.nativeamericanembassy.net/www.lenni-lenape.com/www/html/LenapeArchives/LenapeSet-01/buzzard.html
">Turkey Buzzard and the Sun</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lenape legend telling why Fox has a black mouth.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><B><A HREF="
http://www.calverley.ca/Part06-Legends/6-009.html
">Weesakaychak and the Ducks</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Cree legends about Fox tricking the Trickster out of a meal.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><B><A HREF="
http://www.calverley.ca/Part06-Legends/6-002.html
">The Foundling Who Was Befriended By Wolves</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Cree legend about a boy who won the hand of a chief's daughter by outwitting a pair of clever foxes.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><B><A HREF="
http://www.native-languages.org/aymarastory.htm
">Fox and Monkey</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Aymara story about two trickster animals.
<BR>

<H2><U>
Recommended Books of Fox Stories from Native American Myth and Legend
</u><BR><font size=2>Our organization earns a commission from any book bought through these links</font>
</u></H2>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1558854282/natilangofthe-20
">Mother Fox and Mr. Coyote</A></B>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Children's book illustrating a Fox story from Mexico about a fox mother using her wits to save her family.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0452276500/natilangofthe-20
">Spirits of the Earth: A Guide to Native American Nature Symbols, Stories, and Ceremonies</A></B>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Book by a Karuk elder about the meanings of Indian animal spirits, including a chapter on foxes.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1555911277/natilangofthe-20
">Native American Animal Stories</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Great collection of American Indian tales about foxes and other animals, told by Abenaki storyteller Joseph Bruchac. 
<BR>




